user_query: I need some exercises involving matrix multiplication; can you help?
generated_question: A sports equipment store sells three types of balls: basketballs, soccer balls, and tennis balls. A survey on a Sunday and Monday recorded the number of each type of ball sold. On Sunday, the store sold 45 basketballs, 60 soccer balls, and 75 tennis balls. On Monday, they sold 50 basketballs, 58 soccer balls, and 80 tennis balls. Represent the number of balls sold with the matrix B = \( \begin{pmatrix} 45 & 60 & 75 \\ 50 & 58 & 80 \end{pmatrix} \). If the price per basketball is $15, per soccer ball is $10, and per tennis ball is $5, represent the prices in a matrix P = \( \begin{pmatrix} 15 \\ 10 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} \). (i) Find the matrix S = BP. (ii) Explain what each element of the matrix S represents. (iii) Calculate the total revenue generated from ball sales over these two days.
citation_1_text: The admission tickets to the Singapore Zoo are $50 for an adult, $36 for a child, and $20 for a senior citizen. On a particular Tuesday, there were 212 adults, 251 children, and 15 senior citizens who visited the Singapore Zoo and on a particular Wednesday, there were 231 adults, 266 children, and 12 senior citizens who visited the Singapore Zoo. The number of visitors on the particular Tuesday and Wednesday can be represented by the matrix V = \begin{pmatrix} 212 & 251 & 15 \\ 231 & 266 & 12 \end{pmatrix}. \text{ (i) Write a } 3 \times 1 \text{ matrix, P, to represent the price of the admission tickets. (ii) Find the matrix } T = VP. \text{ (iii) Explain what each of the elements represents. (iv) Find the total amount collected from the sales of the tickets for the 2 days.}
citation_2_text: Two outlets of a coffee chain sell three different types of coffee: espresso, flat white and mocha. The table shows the number of cups of each type of coffee sold on a particular day. Outlet A: Espresso 30, Flat White 30, Mocha 35; Outlet B: Espresso x, Flat White x + 2, Mocha 40. This information can be represented by the matrix \( P = \begin{pmatrix} 30 & 30 & 35 \\ x & x+2 & 40 \end{pmatrix} \). The coffee chain sells a cup of espresso at $2.50, a cup of flat white at $4 and a cup of mocha at $5.50. This information can be represented by the matrix \( Q = \begin{pmatrix} 2.5 \\ 4 \\ 5.5 \end{pmatrix} \). (a) Find, in terms of x, the matrix \( R = PQ \).
